            <h2 id="what-is-semaglutide">What Is Semaglutide?</h2>
            <p>
              Semaglutide is a GLP-1 (glucagon-like peptide-1) receptor agonist that has transformed the field
              of medical weight loss. Developed by Novo Nordisk, it is available as <strong>Wegovy</strong> for
              chronic weight management and <strong>Ozempic</strong> for type 2 diabetes. Wegovy received FDA
              approval for weight loss in June 2021 and has since become one of the most prescribed weight loss
              medications in the United States.
            </p>
            <p>
              Semaglutide was the first GLP-1 medication to demonstrate dramatic weight loss results in clinical
              trials, paving the way for a new era in obesity medicine. It has the longest track record among
              the newer GLP-1 weight loss medications and the most robust cardiovascular safety data.
            </p>

            <h2 id="how-it-works">How Does Semaglutide Work?</h2>
            <p>
              Semaglutide mimics the natural hormone GLP-1, which your body produces in the gut after eating.
              By activating GLP-1 receptors throughout the body, semaglutide produces several effects that
              promote weight loss:
            </p>
            <ul>
              <li><strong>Appetite suppression:</strong> Semaglutide acts on appetite centers in the brain
                (hypothalamus) to reduce hunger and food cravings.</li>
              <li><strong>Delayed gastric emptying:</strong> Food stays in the stomach longer, increasing
                feelings of fullness and satisfaction after smaller meals.</li>
              <li><strong>Improved insulin sensitivity:</strong> Semaglutide enhances the body's response
                to insulin, improving blood sugar regulation.</li>
            </ul>

            <h2 id="clinical-results">Clinical Evidence: The STEP Trial Program</h2>
            <p>
              Semaglutide's weight loss efficacy has been extensively studied in the <strong>STEP</strong> clinical trial program:
            </p>

            <h3>STEP 1 Trial</h3>
            <ul>
              <li>Participants on semaglutide 2.4 mg lost an average of <strong>14.9% of their body weight</strong></li>
              <li>Over <strong>one-third</strong> of participants lost 20% or more of their body weight</li>
              <li>Significant improvements in waist circumference and blood pressure</li>
            </ul>

            <h3>SELECT Trial (Cardiovascular Outcomes)</h3>
            <p>
              The groundbreaking SELECT trial demonstrated that semaglutide reduced the risk of major
              adverse cardiovascular events (heart attack, stroke, or cardiovascular death) by
              <strong>20%</strong> in adults with overweight or obesity and established cardiovascular disease.
            </p>

